🔐 What is an XML Signature?

An XML Digital Signature is a cryptographic signature added inside an XML document to prove:

✅ The message was really sent by the Identity Provider (ADFS)

✅ The message was not modified in transit

✅ The sender cannot deny sending it (non-repudiation)

In SAML:

👉 ADFS signs the SAML Response
👉 Rails verifies the signature

🧠 Why Do We Need It?

Imagine this attack:

Hacker intercepts SAML response and changes:

<Attribute Name="role">
  <AttributeValue>admin</AttributeValue>
</Attribute>


Without signature verification, your app would grant admin access 😨

XML Signature prevents this.

🔑 How XML Signature Works (High Level)

It uses:

Public/Private key cryptography

X.509 certificates

SHA hashing

RSA signing

🏗 Real SAML Security Flow
Step 1️⃣ ADFS Has a Private Key

Stored securely on ADFS server.

It also publishes a public certificate.

Step 2️⃣ ADFS Signs the SAML Assertion

It:

Takes the XML

Generates a hash

Encrypts the hash with its private key

Attaches signature to XML

Example (simplified):

<samlp:Response>
  <saml:Assertion>
    ...
  </saml:Assertion>

  <ds:Signature>
    <ds:SignedInfo>...</ds:SignedInfo>
    <ds:SignatureValue>ABC123XYZ...</ds:SignatureValue>
    <ds:KeyInfo>...</ds:KeyInfo>
  </ds:Signature>
</samlp:Response>


That <ds:Signature> block is the XML Digital Signature.

Step 3️⃣ Rails Verifies It

Rails uses:

ADFS public certificate

Cryptographic verification

If:

Hash matches

Certificate is trusted

Signature matches

Then:

👉 Authentication is valid.

If not:

❌ Reject login

🧠 What Is Inside XML Signature?

Main parts:

1️⃣ SignedInfo

What part of XML was signed.

2️⃣ SignatureValue

The encrypted hash.

3️⃣ KeyInfo

Information about the certificate.

🔐 How Rails Verifies It

In Rails (using omniauth-saml + ruby-saml):

settings.idp_cert = ENV['ADFS_PUBLIC_CERT']


Behind the scenes:

Ruby-SAML extracts signature

Validates using OpenSSL

Verifies against ADFS certificate

If invalid → authentication fails.

💥 Real Interview-Level Explanation

If interviewer asks:

How is SAML secured?

You say:

SAML responses are secured using XML Digital Signatures. The Identity Provider signs the SAML assertion using its private key. Our Rails application verifies the signature using the IdP’s public X.509 certificate. This ensures message integrity, authenticity, and prevents tampering or replay attacks.

🔥 That’s strong.

🚨 Important Security Checks You Must Know

A senior engineer must validate:

Signature validity

Issuer matches expected IdP

Audience matches SP entity ID

NotBefore / NotOnOrAfter timestamps

InResponseTo matches request ID

Not just signature.

🧠 Visual Mental Model
ADFS Private Key  →  Sign SAML XML
Rails Public Cert →  Verify Signature


If someone modifies even 1 character in XML:

Signature validation fails.

🔥 Very Important: Certificate Rotation

ADFS certificates expire.

When they rotate:

IT team updates certificate

Rails app must update stored public certificate

Otherwise logins break

You must mention this in interviews.

